The maximum expiry of a presigned URL depends on how it was signed. IAM user credentials allow up to 7 days, but STS temporary credentials (Lambda, EC2 instance role) are limited to the session duration.

```javascript
import { S3Client, GetObjectCommand } from '@aws-sdk/client-s3';
import { getSignedUrl } from '@aws-sdk/s3-request-presigner';

const client = new S3Client({ region: 'us-east-1' });

// In Lambda: max expiry = remaining Lambda execution time (usually 15 min)
// With IAM role: max expiry = STS session duration (default 1 hour)
// With IAM user: max expiry = 7 days (604800 seconds)
const url = await getSignedUrl(client, new GetObjectCommand({
  Bucket: 'my-bucket',
  Key: 'file.pdf',
}), {
  expiresIn: 3600,  // 1 hour
});
```

If you need long-lived presigned URLs from Lambda, create an IAM user specifically for URL signing (with minimal S3 permissions) and use its credentials. Or use CloudFront signed URLs with a custom policy — they support expiry up to years.

Gotcha: presigned URLs include the signing credentials. If you rotate or delete those credentials, all URLs signed with them become invalid immediately.

DynamoDB Query requires the partition key (equality). You can optionally filter on sort key. To query by different access patterns, you need GSIs.

```javascript
import { DynamoDBClient } from '@aws-sdk/client-dynamodb';
import { DynamoDBDocumentClient, QueryCommand } from '@aws-sdk/lib-dynamodb';

const ddb = DynamoDBDocumentClient.from(new DynamoDBClient({}));

// Table: PK=userId, SK=timestamp
// This works — query by PK with SK range
const result = await ddb.send(new QueryCommand({
  TableName: 'Orders',
  KeyConditionExpression: 'userId = :uid AND #ts BETWEEN :start AND :end',
  ExpressionAttributeNames: { '#ts': 'timestamp' },
  ExpressionAttributeValues: {
    ':uid': 'user123',
    ':start': '2024-01-01',
    ':end': '2024-12-31',
  },
}));

// This does NOT work — can't query by sort key alone
// To find "all orders today" across all users, you need:
// 1. A GSI with date as partition key
// 2. A Scan with filter (expensive, avoid)
```

Design DynamoDB tables around your access patterns first. If you need to query by a non-key attribute, create a GSI. Each table supports up to 20 GSIs.

Standard SQS queues guarantee at-least-once delivery. Your consumer must handle duplicate messages gracefully.

```javascript
// Lambda SQS handler with idempotency
import { DynamoDBClient, PutItemCommand } from '@aws-sdk/client-dynamodb';

const ddb = new DynamoDBClient({});

export const handler = async (event) => {
  for (const record of event.Records) {
    const messageId = record.messageId;
    const body = JSON.parse(record.body);

    // Idempotency check using DynamoDB conditional write
    try {
      await ddb.send(new PutItemCommand({
        TableName: 'ProcessedMessages',
        Item: {
          messageId: { S: messageId },
          processedAt: { N: String(Date.now()) },
          ttl: { N: String(Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000) + 86400) }, // 24h TTL
        },
        ConditionExpression: 'attribute_not_exists(messageId)',
      }));
    } catch (e) {
      if (e.name === 'ConditionalCheckFailedException') {
        console.log(`Duplicate message ${messageId}, skipping`);
        continue;
      }
      throw e;
    }

    // Process the message
    await processOrder(body);
  }
};
```

SQS FIFO queues provide exactly-once processing but are limited to 300 messages/second (3000 with batching). Choose standard queues + idempotency for high throughput.

Lambda environment variables are stored in plaintext in the function configuration. Anyone with `lambda:GetFunctionConfiguration` can see them.

```bash
# Anyone with this permission can see all env vars
aws lambda get-function-configuration --function-name my-func \
  --query 'Environment.Variables'
```

Use Secrets Manager or SSM Parameter Store instead:

```javascript
import { SecretsManagerClient, GetSecretValueCommand } from '@aws-sdk/client-secrets-manager';

const client = new SecretsManagerClient({});

// Cache the secret outside the handler for reuse across invocations
let cachedSecret;
const getSecret = async () => {
  if (!cachedSecret) {
    const response = await client.send(new GetSecretValueCommand({
      SecretId: process.env.SECRET_ARN,  // Only the ARN in env vars
    }));
    cachedSecret = JSON.parse(response.SecretString);
  }
  return cachedSecret;
};

export const handler = async (event) => {
  const secrets = await getSecret();
  const dbUrl = secrets.DATABASE_URL;
  // ...
};
```

The Lambda Powertools parameters utility provides built-in caching and auto-refresh:
```javascript
import { getSecret } from '@aws-lambda-powertools/parameters/secrets';
const dbUrl = await getSecret('my-app/db-url', { maxAge: 300 });
```

Fargate tasks in private subnets have no internet access by default. They can't pull container images from ECR or reach any external APIs without a NAT Gateway or VPC endpoints.

```typescript
// CDK — Fargate with proper networking
const vpc = new ec2.Vpc(this, 'Vpc', {
  maxAzs: 2,
  natGateways: 1,  // NAT Gateway for private subnet internet access
  // Costs ~$32/month per NAT Gateway + data transfer
});

// Cheaper alternative: VPC endpoints for AWS services
vpc.addInterfaceEndpoint('EcrEndpoint', {
  service: ec2.InterfaceVpcEndpointAwsService.ECR,
});
vpc.addInterfaceEndpoint('EcrDockerEndpoint', {
  service: ec2.InterfaceVpcEndpointAwsService.ECR_DOCKER,
});
vpc.addGatewayEndpoint('S3Endpoint', {
  service: ec2.GatewayVpcEndpointAwsService.S3,
});
vpc.addInterfaceEndpoint('CloudWatchEndpoint', {
  service: ec2.InterfaceVpcEndpointAwsService.CLOUDWATCH_LOGS,
});
```

VPC endpoints avoid NAT Gateway data transfer costs ($0.045/GB) but each interface endpoint costs ~$7.20/month per AZ. For small workloads, a single NAT Gateway is simpler. For large data transfer, VPC endpoints are cheaper.

Secrets Manager costs $0.40/secret/month plus $0.05 per 10,000 API calls. Calling GetSecretValue on every Lambda invocation gets expensive at scale.

```javascript
// Bad — API call every invocation
export const handler = async () => {
  const secret = await client.send(new GetSecretValueCommand({
    SecretId: 'my-secret'
  }));
  // 1M invocations/month = $5 in API calls alone
};

// Good — cache with TTL
let cache = { value: null, expiry: 0 };

export const handler = async () => {
  if (Date.now() > cache.expiry) {
    const response = await client.send(new GetSecretValueCommand({
      SecretId: 'my-secret'
    }));
    cache = {
      value: JSON.parse(response.SecretString),
      expiry: Date.now() + 300_000, // 5 minute cache
    };
  }
  const secret = cache.value;
};
```

Alternative: use SSM Parameter Store SecureString — free for standard parameters (up to 10,000), $0.05 per 10,000 API calls for advanced. No per-parameter charge. Use Secrets Manager only when you need automatic rotation.

Cross-account access needs permissions on both sides: the source account must allow assuming the role, and the target account's role must trust the source.

```json
// Target account (Account B) — Role trust policy
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Principal": {
      "AWS": "arn:aws:iam::111111111111:root"  // Account A
    },
    "Action": "sts:AssumeRole",
    "Condition": {
      "StringEquals": {
        "sts:ExternalId": "unique-external-id"  // Confused deputy protection
      }
    }
  }]
}

// Target account (Account B) — Role permissions policy
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Action": ["s3:GetObject", "s3:ListBucket"],
    "Resource": ["arn:aws:s3:::shared-bucket", "arn:aws:s3:::shared-bucket/*"]
  }]
}
```

```json
// Source account (Account A) — IAM user/role policy
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [{
    "Effect": "Allow",
    "Action": "sts:AssumeRole",
    "Resource": "arn:aws:iam::222222222222:role/CrossAccountReadRole"
  }]
}
```

The `ExternalId` condition prevents confused deputy attacks. Always use it for third-party access. For S3 specifically, you can also use bucket policies with cross-account principals as an alternative to role assumption.

EventBridge can invoke targets cross-service, but the target must grant EventBridge permission to invoke it. Without a resource policy, the rule silently fails.

```typescript
// CDK — EventBridge rule targeting Lambda
const rule = new events.Rule(this, 'ScheduleRule', {
  schedule: events.Schedule.rate(cdk.Duration.hours(1)),
});

// CDK auto-adds the Lambda resource policy, but CloudFormation doesn't!
rule.addTarget(new targets.LambdaFunction(fn));

// Manual CloudFormation — you must add this:
new lambda.CfnPermission(this, 'EventBridgePermission', {
  action: 'lambda:InvokeFunction',
  functionName: fn.functionName,
  principal: 'events.amazonaws.com',
  sourceArn: rule.ruleArn,
});
```

This applies to all EventBridge targets: Lambda, SNS, SQS, Step Functions, API destinations. Each target type needs its own resource policy format. Without it, EventBridge logs the failure in the rule's metrics but there's no error in CloudWatch Logs.

CDK generates CloudFormation logical IDs from the construct tree path. Renaming constructs or moving them in the tree changes the logical ID, causing resource replacement.

```typescript
// Original — logical ID: MyApiHandlerABC123
const handler = new lambda.Function(this, 'MyApiHandler', { ... });

// Renamed — logical ID changes, Lambda is REPLACED (new ARN, lost config)
const handler = new lambda.Function(this, 'ApiRequestHandler', { ... });

// Fix: override the logical ID to keep it stable
const handler = new lambda.Function(this, 'ApiRequestHandler', { ... });
const cfnFn = handler.node.defaultChild as lambda.CfnFunction;
cfnFn.overrideLogicalId('MyApiHandlerABC123');
```

Pro tip: before refactoring CDK code, run `cdk diff` to check for replacements. Resources marked with `[~]` are updated in-place, `[-]`/`[+]` means replacement.

For stateful resources (databases, S3 buckets), always set `removalPolicy: cdk.RemovalPolicy.RETAIN` to prevent accidental deletion on ID changes.

Aurora Serverless v2 scales between a minimum and maximum ACU (Aurora Capacity Units). The minimum is 0.5 ACU ($0.06/hour ≈ $43/month), not zero.

```typescript
// CDK — Aurora Serverless v2
const cluster = new rds.DatabaseCluster(this, 'DB', {
  engine: rds.DatabaseClusterEngine.auroraPostgres({
    version: rds.AuroraPostgresEngineVersion.VER_16_1,
  }),
  serverlessV2MinCapacity: 0.5,  // Min: 0.5 ACU ($43/month)
  serverlessV2MaxCapacity: 16,    // Max: 16 ACU
  writer: rds.ClusterInstance.serverlessV2('writer'),
  readers: [
    rds.ClusterInstance.serverlessV2('reader', {
      scaleWithWriter: true,
    }),
  ],
});
```

For dev/staging where you want true zero cost when idle, consider:
- **Aurora Serverless v1** (being deprecated) had scale-to-zero
- **RDS with stop/start**: Schedule `aws rds stop-db-instance` for non-business hours
- **Neon Postgres**: Serverless Postgres that actually scales to zero (not AWS-native)

Aurora Serverless v2 is cost-effective for production workloads with variable traffic, but overkill for dev environments that sit idle most of the time.

Lambda reuses execution environments ("warm" containers). Module-level variables, database connections, and temp files persist between invocations of the same container.

```javascript
// Module-level: initialized once, reused across invocations
import { DynamoDBClient } from '@aws-sdk/client-dynamodb';
const ddb = new DynamoDBClient({}); // Connection pool reused — GOOD

let requestCount = 0; // Persists across invocations — could be a BUG

export const handler = async (event) => {
  requestCount++; // This accumulates across invocations!
  console.log(`Request #${requestCount}`); // Could print 1, 2, 3...

  // Don't assume clean /tmp
  // Previous invocation's temp files may still exist
  const files = fs.readdirSync('/tmp');
  console.log('Existing temp files:', files);

  // Don't assume fresh environment variables
  // If you update env vars, existing warm containers keep old values
  // until they're recycled
};
```

Leverage reuse for performance (SDK clients, DB connections, cached data). But never rely on it for correctness — any invocation could be a cold start with fresh state. Always initialize per-request state inside the handler.

A Lambda function needs two types of permissions: its execution role (what Lambda can do) and resource policies on other services (who can invoke Lambda).

```typescript
// CDK example
const fn = new lambda.Function(this, 'MyFunc', {
  runtime: lambda.Runtime.NODEJS_20_X,
  handler: 'index.handler',
  code: lambda.Code.fromAsset('lambda'),
});

// Execution role: what the Lambda can access
const table = new dynamodb.Table(this, 'Table', { ... });
table.grantReadWriteData(fn); // Adds DynamoDB permissions to execution role

// Resource policy: who can invoke the Lambda
fn.addPermission('ApiGatewayInvoke', {
  principal: new iam.ServicePrincipal('apigateway.amazonaws.com'),
  sourceArn: api.arnForExecuteApi(),
});

// Common mistake: adding invoke permission to the execution role
// This does NOT allow API Gateway to invoke the function!
fn.role.addToPrincipalPolicy(new iam.PolicyStatement({
  actions: ['lambda:InvokeFunction'],
  resources: [fn.functionArn],
})); // WRONG — this lets Lambda invoke ITSELF, not let others invoke it
```

Execution role = outbound permissions. Resource policy = inbound permissions. Services like API Gateway, EventBridge, S3, and SNS need resource policies (or IAM role-based invocation) to trigger Lambda.

On-demand pricing is $1.25 per million write request units vs $0.00065 per WCU/hour for provisioned. At steady traffic, provisioned with auto-scaling is significantly cheaper.

```typescript
// On-demand — simple but expensive at scale
const table = new dynamodb.Table(this, 'Table', {
  billingMode: dynamodb.BillingMode.PAY_PER_REQUEST,
  // 100 writes/sec sustained = ~$330/month
});

// Provisioned with auto-scaling — cheaper at steady traffic
const table = new dynamodb.Table(this, 'Table', {
  billingMode: dynamodb.BillingMode.PROVISIONED,
  readCapacity: 25,
  writeCapacity: 25,
});
table.autoScaleWriteCapacity({
  minCapacity: 25,
  maxCapacity: 500,
}).scaleOnUtilization({ targetUtilizationPercent: 70 });
// 100 writes/sec sustained = ~$48/month
```

Rule of thumb:
- Use **on-demand** for: unpredictable traffic, new tables (unknown patterns), dev/staging, spiky workloads
- Use **provisioned** for: steady production traffic, cost-sensitive workloads, predictable patterns

You can switch between modes, but after switching to on-demand, you must wait 24 hours before switching back to provisioned.

SNS subscription filter policies let you route messages to specific subscribers without invoking all of them. But the filter syntax has non-obvious behavior.

```json
// Filter policy — subscription receives only matching messages
{
  "eventType": ["order.created", "order.updated"],
  "region": ["us-east-1"],
  "amount": [{"numeric": [">", 100]}]
}

// Message attributes MUST match the filter keys:
// MessageAttributes: {
//   eventType: { DataType: 'String', StringValue: 'order.created' },
//   region: { DataType: 'String', StringValue: 'us-east-1' },
//   amount: { DataType: 'Number', StringValue: '150' }
// }
```

Gotchas:
1. **Filter on body**: By default, filters only work on MessageAttributes, NOT the message body. Enable `FilterPolicyScope: MessageBody` to filter on body content.
2. **Missing attribute = no match**: If a message doesn't have the attribute, the filter rejects it (unless you use `[{"exists": false}]`)
3. **OR within, AND across**: Values in an array are OR'd; keys are AND'd
4. **No regex**: Only exact match, prefix, numeric comparisons, and exists
5. **150 keys max**: Total filter complexity is limited

Provisioned concurrency pre-initializes Lambda execution environments. But if traffic exceeds provisioned capacity, additional invocations still cold-start normally.

```typescript
// CDK — provisioned concurrency
const fn = new lambda.Function(this, 'Api', { ... });

const alias = fn.addAlias('live');
alias.addAutoScaling({
  minCapacity: 5,     // Always 5 warm instances
  maxCapacity: 50,    // Scale up to 50
}).scaleOnUtilization({ utilizationTarget: 0.7 });

// IMPORTANT: provisioned concurrency is per-alias/version, not per-function
// You MUST use aliases or versions, not $LATEST
```

Cost: $0.0000041667/GB-second (in addition to regular invocation costs). 5 instances at 512MB running 24/7 ≈ $90/month.

Gotchas:
- Takes 3-5 minutes to provision — not instant
- Counts against your account's concurrency limit
- Cannot be set on `$LATEST` — must use a published version or alias
- Auto-scaling reacts to utilization, not request count — a burst can still cause cold starts before scaling kicks in

Lambda function URLs are public HTTPS endpoints. Setting `authType: NONE` means literally anyone on the internet can invoke your function with no rate limiting.

```typescript
// DANGEROUS — publicly accessible, no auth, no rate limiting
const fnUrl = fn.addFunctionUrl({
  authType: lambda.FunctionUrlAuthType.NONE,
});

// Better — IAM auth (requires sigv4 signed requests)
const fnUrl = fn.addFunctionUrl({
  authType: lambda.FunctionUrlAuthType.AWS_IAM,
});

// If you need public access, add your own auth:
export const handler = async (event) => {
  const authHeader = event.headers?.authorization;
  if (!authHeader || !verifyToken(authHeader)) {
    return { statusCode: 401, body: 'Unauthorized' };
  }
  // ... handle request
};
```

Function URLs have no WAF integration, no API keys, no usage plans, and no request validation. For production APIs, use API Gateway instead. Function URLs are best for webhooks, internal tools, and quick prototypes where you implement your own auth.

Since December 2020, S3 provides strong read-after-write consistency for all operations. However, S3 list operations are still eventually consistent for bucket-level listing (ListBuckets).

```javascript
// These are strongly consistent:
await s3.send(new PutObjectCommand({ Bucket: 'b', Key: 'file.txt', Body: 'data' }));
const obj = await s3.send(new GetObjectCommand({ Bucket: 'b', Key: 'file.txt' }));
// obj always reflects the latest PUT

// ListObjectsV2 within a bucket IS consistent:
const list = await s3.send(new ListObjectsV2Command({ Bucket: 'b', Prefix: 'files/' }));
// Will include the newly uploaded file

// But: ListBuckets can be eventually consistent
const buckets = await s3.send(new ListBucketsCommand({}));
// A just-created bucket might not appear yet
```

The old workarounds (add delay after write, use GET to verify before LIST) are no longer needed for object operations. But if your code depends on ListBuckets immediately after CreateBucket, add a retry.

Lambda timeout errors mean the function exceeded its configured timeout (default 3 seconds, max 15 minutes). The function is killed without running finally blocks or cleanup.

```javascript
// Common cause 1: Unresolved promise / callback not called
export const handler = async (event) => {
  const result = someFunction(); // Missing await!
  return result; // Returns a Promise object, not the result
};

// Common cause 2: VPC cold start (deprecated concern — fixed with Hyperplane)
// Old: Lambda in VPC needed ENI creation (10-30s)
// New: <1s VPC setup, but DNS resolution can still be slow

// Common cause 3: Waiting for a connection that never completes
export const handler = async (event) => {
  // Connection to RDS in wrong security group — hangs until timeout
  const connection = await pool.connect();
};

// Fix: Set shorter timeouts on outbound connections
const client = new DynamoDBClient({
  requestHandler: new NodeHttpHandler({
    connectionTimeout: 3000,  // 3s connection timeout
    socketTimeout: 3000,      // 3s socket timeout
  }),
});
```

Debugging steps:
1. Check if it's a cold start (look for `Init Duration` in CloudWatch)
2. Add timeout/deadline logging at key points
3. Check security groups allow outbound traffic to the target
4. Verify DNS resolution works (especially in VPC)

Lambda kills functions that exceed their configured memory. The function exits with signal 9 (SIGKILL) and logs show exit code 137.

```
Error: Runtime exited with error: signal: killed
RequestId: xxx-xxx
Runtime.ExitError
```

```javascript
// Diagnose memory usage
export const handler = async (event) => {
  const used = process.memoryUsage();
  console.log('Memory usage:', {
    rss: `${Math.round(used.rss / 1024 / 1024)}MB`,
    heapUsed: `${Math.round(used.heapUsed / 1024 / 1024)}MB`,
    heapTotal: `${Math.round(used.heapTotal / 1024 / 1024)}MB`,
  });

  // Common cause: loading large files/datasets into memory
  // Fix: stream processing instead of loading entirely
  const stream = (await s3.send(new GetObjectCommand({ Bucket, Key }))).Body;
  // Process stream chunk by chunk instead of: const data = await stream.transformToString();
};
```

Fixes:
1. Increase memory (up to 10,240 MB)
2. Stream large files instead of buffering
3. Use `/tmp` (10GB, or EFS) for large files
4. Set Node.js `--max-old-space-size` to 90% of Lambda memory
5. Use Lambda Power Tuning tool to find optimal memory setting

Your read/write request rate exceeds the table's provisioned capacity. With on-demand tables, you can still get throttled during sudden spikes (5x previous peak within 30 minutes).

```javascript
// Implement exponential backoff (AWS SDK v3 does this automatically)
import { DynamoDBClient } from '@aws-sdk/client-dynamodb';

const client = new DynamoDBClient({
  maxAttempts: 5,  // SDK retries with exponential backoff
});

// For batch operations, handle unprocessed items
const result = await client.send(new BatchWriteItemCommand({ RequestItems: items }));
if (Object.keys(result.UnprocessedItems || {}).length > 0) {
  // Retry unprocessed items with backoff
  await retryUnprocessedItems(result.UnprocessedItems);
}
```

Common causes:
1. **Hot partition**: Single partition key getting all traffic. Fix: add random suffix to partition key
2. **Burst capacity exhausted**: DynamoDB saves unused capacity for 5 minutes of bursts
3. **On-demand scaling delay**: Takes ~5 min to scale to 2x previous peak
4. **GSI throttling**: GSI has separate throughput. A throttled GSI throttles the base table writes

Monitor with CloudWatch: `ConsumedReadCapacityUnits`, `ConsumedWriteCapacityUnits`, `ThrottledRequests`.

Lambda's `/tmp` directory defaults to 512MB (configurable up to 10GB since 2022). If you write files without cleanup, subsequent invocations on the same warm container accumulate files until it's full.

```javascript
// Bad: files accumulate across warm invocations
export const handler = async (event) => {
  const tempFile = `/tmp/data-${Date.now()}.json`;
  fs.writeFileSync(tempFile, JSON.stringify(largeData));
  // Process file...
  // Forgot to delete! Next invocation adds another file.
};

// Good: clean up temp files
export const handler = async (event) => {
  const tempFile = `/tmp/data-${Date.now()}.json`;
  try {
    fs.writeFileSync(tempFile, JSON.stringify(largeData));
    await processFile(tempFile);
  } finally {
    fs.unlinkSync(tempFile);  // Always clean up
  }
};

// Good: use a fixed filename to overwrite
export const handler = async (event) => {
  fs.writeFileSync('/tmp/working-data.json', JSON.stringify(data));
  // Same file overwritten each invocation
};
```

Increase `/tmp` size in the function config:
```typescript
new lambda.Function(this, 'Fn', {
  ephemeralStorageSize: cdk.Size.mebibytes(2048), // Up to 10240 MB
});
```

CDK asset bundling (for Lambda, ECS, etc.) fails silently or with cryptic errors when Docker isn't running or the build command fails.

```typescript
// NodejsFunction uses esbuild — can fail if dependencies are wrong
const fn = new NodejsFunction(this, 'Handler', {
  entry: 'src/handler.ts',
  bundling: {
    externalModules: ['@aws-sdk/*'], // Exclude SDK (available in Lambda runtime)
    nodeModules: ['sharp'],  // Install these instead of bundling
    minify: true,
    sourceMap: true,
  },
});
```

Common bundling errors:

1. **Docker not running**: CDK falls back to Docker bundling when local tools aren't available
```bash
# Fix: install esbuild locally
npm install esbuild
```

2. **Module not found during bundling**: Import path issue
```bash
# Debug: try bundling manually
npx esbuild src/handler.ts --bundle --platform=node --outfile=dist/handler.js
```

3. **Native module bundling fails**: Some modules need `nodeModules` instead of bundling
```typescript
bundling: {
  nodeModules: ['bcrypt', 'sharp'], // Install via npm, don't bundle
}
```

4. **Asset hash changed unexpectedly**: `.dockerignore` or `exclude` patterns changed
```typescript
bundling: {
  commandHooks: {
    beforeBundling: (i, o) => [`echo 'Building...'`],
  },
}
```

SQS makes a message invisible after delivery for the visibility timeout period (default 30 seconds). If your consumer doesn't delete the message before the timeout, it reappears and gets processed again.

```javascript
// Problem: processing takes longer than visibility timeout
// Message reappears and another consumer processes it = duplicate!

// Fix 1: Set visibility timeout > max processing time
// Lambda: SQS trigger automatically sets visibility to 6x the function timeout

// Fix 2: Extend visibility timeout during processing
import { SQSClient, ChangeMessageVisibilityCommand } from '@aws-sdk/client-sqs';

const sqs = new SQSClient({});

async function processWithHeartbeat(message) {
  const interval = setInterval(async () => {
    await sqs.send(new ChangeMessageVisibilityCommand({
      QueueUrl: QUEUE_URL,
      ReceiptHandle: message.ReceiptHandle,
      VisibilityTimeout: 60, // Extend by 60 seconds
    }));
  }, 30_000); // Every 30 seconds

  try {
    await processMessage(message);
    await sqs.send(new DeleteMessageCommand({
      QueueUrl: QUEUE_URL,
      ReceiptHandle: message.ReceiptHandle,
    }));
  } finally {
    clearInterval(interval);
  }
}
```

For Lambda SQS triggers: set the Lambda timeout to less than 1/6 of the queue's visibility timeout. Lambda auto-extends visibility, but if it crashes, the message returns after the timeout.

RDS instances have a max connection limit based on instance size. Lambda functions, with their massive concurrency, can easily exhaust the connection pool.

```
max_connections formula (PostgreSQL):
db.t4g.micro:  ~80 connections
db.t4g.small:  ~170 connections
db.t4g.medium: ~340 connections
db.r6g.large:  ~1600 connections
```

```javascript
// Problem: each Lambda invocation opens a new connection
// 100 concurrent Lambdas = 100 connections

// Solution 1: RDS Proxy (best for Lambda)
// RDS Proxy pools and reuses connections
const pool = new Pool({
  connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL, // Points to RDS Proxy endpoint
  max: 1, // Each Lambda only needs 1 connection
  idleTimeoutMillis: 0, // Never idle-timeout (Lambda manages lifecycle)
});

// Solution 2: Connection pooling with Prisma
// prisma/schema.prisma
// datasource db {
//   provider = "postgresql"
//   url = env("DATABASE_URL")
//   relationMode = "prisma"
// }
// In Lambda: set connection_limit=1 in URL
// DATABASE_URL="postgresql://...?connection_limit=1"
```

RDS Proxy costs ~15% on top of the RDS instance price but handles connection pooling, failover, and IAM authentication. It's almost always worth it for Lambda → RDS workloads.

