Use SQS between Lambda functions for decoupled, reliable async processing with automatic retries and dead letter queues.

```typescript
// CDK — Async processing pipeline
const mainQueue = new sqs.Queue(this, 'ProcessingQueue', {
  visibilityTimeout: cdk.Duration.minutes(6), // 6x Lambda timeout
  retentionPeriod: cdk.Duration.days(14),
  deadLetterQueue: {
    maxReceiveCount: 3,
    queue: new sqs.Queue(this, 'DLQ', {
      retentionPeriod: cdk.Duration.days(14),
    }),
  },
});

// API handler sends to queue
const apiFn = new lambda.Function(this, 'ApiFn', {
  timeout: cdk.Duration.seconds(10),
});
mainQueue.grantSendMessages(apiFn);

// Worker processes from queue
const workerFn = new lambda.Function(this, 'WorkerFn', {
  timeout: cdk.Duration.minutes(1),
  reservedConcurrentExecutions: 10, // Limit concurrency to protect downstream
});

workerFn.addEventSource(new SqsEventSource(mainQueue, {
  batchSize: 10,
  maxBatchingWindow: cdk.Duration.seconds(5),
  reportBatchItemFailures: true, // Partial failure support
}));
```

This pattern provides: automatic retries (message returns to queue on failure), backpressure (reserved concurrency limits parallel processing), dead letter queue (captures permanently failed messages), and decoupling (API returns fast, processing happens async).

