Lambda response streaming sends data to the client as it's generated, bypassing the 6MB response limit and reducing time-to-first-byte.

```javascript
import { Readable } from 'stream';
import { pipeline } from 'stream/promises';

export const handler = awslambda.streamifyResponse(async (event, responseStream) => {
  // Set content type
  const metadata = {
    statusCode: 200,
    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
  };
  responseStream = awslambda.HttpResponseStream.from(responseStream, metadata);

  // Stream large dataset
  const dbStream = await fetchLargeDataset();

  responseStream.write('[');
  let first = true;
  for await (const record of dbStream) {
    if (!first) responseStream.write(',');
    responseStream.write(JSON.stringify(record));
    first = false;
  }
  responseStream.write(']');
  responseStream.end();
});

// SSE (Server-Sent Events) pattern
export const sseHandler = awslambda.streamifyResponse(async (event, responseStream) => {
  const metadata = {
    statusCode: 200,
    headers: {
      'Content-Type': 'text/event-stream',
      'Cache-Control': 'no-cache',
    },
  };
  responseStream = awslambda.HttpResponseStream.from(responseStream, metadata);

  for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
    responseStream.write(`data: ${JSON.stringify({ progress: i * 10 })}\n\n`);
    await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 1000));
  }
  responseStream.end();
});
```

Requires Lambda function URL (not API Gateway REST API). API Gateway HTTP API supports streaming. Maximum streamed response: 20MB (soft limit, can be increased).

